    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A solid red light next to the globe icon on your router is the universal sign of a **frozen or overheated router**, and in the grand scheme of the internet, it is a very specific kind of problem.\n\nFirst, you must **unplug the router from the wall outlet** immediately and wait at least 15 minutes to let the internal components cool down. If you plug it back in while it's still hot, you risk frying the motherboard, which is a very expensive mistake.\n\nOnce it's cooled, check the power cable and the Ethernet cable connecting the router to your computer or modem. If the lights are still red, try plugging the router into a different outlet to rule out a tripped breaker or a faulty power strip. If the red light persists after cooling and checking cables, the router likely has a hardware failure or a firmware glitch that requires a factory reset.\n\n**However**, if you are a **goblin**, you might have a different problem entirely. Perhaps your internet is down because you've been **stuck in a loop of doom-scrolling** and your brain has become a **glitchy router** itself. In that case, the solution is not to unplug the router, but",
